722074f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 38th Street
722074f-a.text:
Park Avenue, north from 38th Street, showing the nearly comgleted New
York Centra. Builcing towering over Grand Central Terminal.
The following buildings in the picture are later to be denolished: the
house shown on the S. W. corner of 39th Street (1933), the S. W. corner
of 40th Street and the two houses adjoining it on the south (1931),
the four houses from the N. E. corner of 39th Street north (1933),
and the Hotel Belnont in the block above the old Murray Hill.
The Princeton Club is the building on the N. W. corner of 39th Street.
Above the house on the N. W. corner of 39th Street one can see a little
bit of the building at 60 East 42nd Street which is about to give
place to the new Lincoln Building.
1928.
Cosmo Photo Co.
MAY BE REPRODUCRD with creait.

722082f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 38th Street
722082f-a.text:
Park Avenue, east side, from 39th to 38th Streets, seen from the
roof of 271 Madison Avenue, and showing the East River in the
background.
77 yark Avenue, on the S.E. corner of 39th Street, was erected in
1924, and 67 Park Avenue, on the N.E. corner of 38th Street, was
completed in 1922 on the site of the old Charles D. Barney
residence. The building in the middle of the block .vas erected
between these two in point of time. East of Park Avenue is
shown the colored tower of Town House Apartments, 108 East 38th
Street, erected in 1930.
The single smoke-stack seen in the background is part of the New
York Steam Corporation's plant on the east side of First Avenue
between 35th and 36th Streets.
December 2, 1931.
P. L. Sperr, Photographer.
NO IEPRODUCTIONS.

722083f-b.text:

These three apartment houses were built during the years 1922-24,

old Charles D. Barney residence, being the first. Behind it
hrises the colored tower of own House Apartments at 108 East

In the foreground the old houses on the S.W. corner of 39th
Street are being demolished.
September 10, 1933.
P. L. Sperr, Photographer.
